      <byline class="print_byline">By Wayne Arnold</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Arnold, Wayne</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Visit by Sec of State Madeleine Albright to North Korea overshadows visit by business delegation from Singapore (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>While Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright was talking missiles and Oscars last week with North Korea's eccentric leader, Kim Jong Il, a less-ballyhooed delegation from one of Asia's early economic miracles, Singapore, was in North Korea to talk business.</p>
        <p>Robin Lau, president of the Singapore Confederation of Industries, said the North Koreans were ''just like China 10 or 15 years ago; they understand that the survival of the country depends on the economy.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>While Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright was talking missiles and Oscars last week with North Korea's eccentric leader, Kim Jong Il, a less-ballyhooed delegation from one of Asia's early economic miracles, Singapore, was in North Korea to talk business.</p>
        <p>Robin Lau, president of the Singapore Confederation of Industries, said the North Koreans were ''just like China 10 or 15 years ago; they understand that the survival of the country depends on the economy.''</p>
        <p>Mr. Lau, who runs a machine-tool company in an authoritarian country where chewing gum is banned, called the Orwellian depictions of North Korea sensational.</p>
        <p>Wayne Arnold</p>
        <p>BUSINESS: DIARY</p>
      </block>
